<%- include("partials/header"); %>

<div class="college-prep-page">
  <!-- Title Section -->
  <div class="prep-title-section">
    <h1>College Preparation</h1>
    <p>
      College applications are stressful and complex - here’s our guide on how to make the most of your application season in three phases: 
    </p>
    <p>
      Preparation, Application, and Finalization
    </p>
  </div>

  <!-- Preparation Section -->
  <div class="prep-section">
    <h2>Preparation</h2>
    <p>
      College applications are a record of everything you did in high school, you want to make the most of your four years. Many people can follow these steps, but if you want to really set yourself apart, reflect on those experiences. They aren’t meant to add another bullet point to your checklist, they’re meant to make you grow as an individual!
    </p>
    <div class="prep-content">
      <div class="prep-item">
        <h3>1.  Academic Excellence</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Take challenging courses in core academic areas:</li>
          <li>English, social studies, mathematics, science, and foreign languages</li>
          <li>Challenge yourself with honors or AP/IB courses when possible</li>
          <li>Maintain a strong GPA throughout all four years</li>
          <li>Keep detailed notes of your academic interests to help inform your college major choice</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="prep-item">
        <h3>2. Extracurricular Development</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Join school clubs aligned with your interests</li>
          <li>Anywhere from sports, arts, politics, etc.</li>
          <li>Seek leadership positions in organizations!</li>
          <li>Volunteer in your community</li>
          <li>Consider part-time jobs or internships</li>
          <li>Start personal projects that showcase your initiative</li>
          <li>Participate in summer programs or academic camps</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="prep-item">
        <h3>3. Career and Major Exploration</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Research potential careers through:</li>
          <li>Job shadowing opportunities</li>
          <li>Informational interviews</li>
          <li>Career aptitude tests</li>
          <li>College major exploration websites</li>
          <li>Consider factors such as:</li>
          <li>Job market demand</li>
          <li>Salary potential</li>
          <li>Work-life balance</li>
          <li>Required education level</li>
          <li>Personal interests and strengths</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Application Section -->
  <div class="application-section">
    <h2>Application</h2>
    <p>You’re in your junior year, what now? Applying to colleges is a confusing process, here’s our step-by-step guide!</p>
    <div class="application-content">
      <div class="application-item">
        <h3>1. Deadline Management</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Create a spreadsheet with:</li>
          <li>College names and locations</li>
          <li>Application deadlines</li>
          <li>Application fees</li>
          <li>Scholarship deadlines</li>
          <li>Financial aid form deadlines</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="application-item">
        <h3>2. SAT & ACT Prep</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Create a structured study schedule for at least one month</li>
          <li>Utilize free resources:</li>
          <li>Khan Academy</li>
          <li>College Board practice tests</li>
          <li>Practice strategies:</li>
          <li>Take full-length practice tests</li>
          <li>Time yourself strictly</li>
          <li>Review all answers thoroughly, correct and incorrect!</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="application-item">
        <h3>3. Test Registration</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Register early for preferred test dates, make sure the score release dates are before your college application deadlines!</li>
          <li>Send scores to colleges</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="application-item">
        <h3>4. Essay</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Address your prompts thoroughly</li>
          <li>Show rather than tell</li>
          <li>Be specific and personal</li>
          <li>Review your essay with as many people as possible</li>
          <li>Submit well before deadlines</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="application-item">
        <h3>5. Letters of Recommendation</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Choose recommenders who know you well</li>
          <li>Provide them with:</li>
            <li>Resume, Activity list, Academic achievements, Specific deadlines, Submission instructions</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="application-item">
        <h3>6. Application Completion - YAY!</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Fill out all sections accurately</li>
          <li>Double-check personal information</li>
          <li>Verify test score and transcript submissions</li>
          <li>Submit well before deadlines</li>
          <li>Keep copies of all materials</li>
          <li>Monitor application status</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Finalization Section -->
  <div class="finalization-section">
    <h2>Finalization</h2>
    <div class="finalization-content">
      <div class="finalization-item">
        <h3>1. Academic Preparation</h3>
        <ul>
          <p>College classes offer more freedom, but it’s essential
            to stay organized. Use a planner or digital calendar 
           to track assignments, exams, and deadlines. 
           Read syllabi thoroughly to understand each 
           professor’s expectations.</p>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="finalization-item">
        <h3>2. Housing</h3>
        <ul>
          <p>Research the different housing options, including dorms, student apartments, conventional apartments, and renting options. Here are some pros and cons for each:</p>
          <li>Dorms: Great for meeting other students and staying close to campus, but may have less privacy.</li>
          <li>Student Apartments: Typically offer more independence and can be more spacious than dorms</li>
          <li>Conventional Apartments: Ideal if you’re looking for total independence, but may require a longer commute.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="finalization-item">
        <h3>3. Moving In</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Make a list of necessities (bedding, toiletries, school supplies, etc.) and avoid overpacking. Remember, you can always buy items once you’re settled in.</li>
          <li>OCoordinate with your roommates if you have any and get familiar with your new space. Bring any important documents you may need and unpack essentials first.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="finalization-item">
        <h3>4. Explore Campus</h3>
        <ul>
          <p>Get to know the campus layout, and find important locations such as </p>
          <li>Libraries</li>
          <li>Dining halls</li>
          <li>Recreational facilities</li>
          <p>Familiarize yourself with where your classes are located before the first day.</p>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="finalization-item">
        <h3>5.   Join Clubs and Make Friends!</h3>
        <ul>
          <p>College is a great opportunity to meet new people. </p>
          <li>Attend club fairs</li>
          <li>Join student organizations</li>
          <li>Participate in campus events</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

